\f1\b Today is the anniversary of the birth of John William Strutt, 3rd Baron Rayleigh
\f2\b0  (1842-1919), 
\f0 \uc0\u55356 \u56812 \u55356 \u56807 
\f2 British scientist who made extensive contributions to both {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoretical_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 theoretical}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 experimental physics}}. He spent all of his academic career at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Cambridge"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 University of Cambridge}}. Among many honours, he received the 1904 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Nobel Prize in Physics}} "for his investigations of the densities of the most important gases and for his discovery of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argon"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 argon}} in connection with these studies." \
Rayleigh provided the first theoretical treatment of the elastic scattering of light by particles much smaller than the light's wavelength, a phenomenon now known as "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh_scattering"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh scattering}}", which notably explains why the sky is blue. He studied and described transverse {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_wave"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 surface waves}} in solids, now known as "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh_wave"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh waves}}". He contributed extensively to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dynamics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 fluid dynamics}}, with concepts such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh_number"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh number}} (a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionless_number"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 dimensionless number}} associated with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_convection"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 natural convection}}), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh_flow"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh flow}}, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh%E2%80%93Taylor_instability"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh\'96Taylor instability}}, and Rayleigh's criterion for the stability of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor%E2%80%93Couette_flow"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Taylor\'96Couette flow}}. He also formulated the circulation theory of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lift_(force)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 aerodynamic lift}}. In {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 optics}}, Rayleigh proposed a well known criterion for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_resolution"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 angular resolution}}. His derivation of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rayleigh%E2%80%93Jeans_law"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rayleigh\'96Jeans law}} for classical black-body radiation later played an important role in birth of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 quantum mechanics}}. \
\

\f0 \uc0\u55356 \u56814 \u55356 \u56825 
\f2  \'c8 oggi l\'92anniversario della nascita di 
\f1\b \cf2 John William Strutt, 3o Barone Rayleigh
\f2\b0  (1842-1919), scienziato britannico che ha dato estensivi contributi sia alla fisica sperimentale che teorica. Ha passato la maggior parte della sua carriera accademica all\'92Universit\'e1 di Cambridge. Tra i numerosi vari altri premi, \'e9 stato insignito del Premio Nobel per la fisica nel 1904 \'93per i suoi studi dei pi\'f9 importanti gas e per la scoperta dell\'92Argon in connessione ai suoi studi\'94.\
Rayleigh fern il primo trattamento teorico della diffusione ottica (scattering) di particelle molto minori della lunghezza d\'92onda della luce, un fenomeno noto oggi come \'93diffusione di Rayleigh\'94, che spiega inoltre perch\'e9 il cielo \'e9 blu. Ha studiato e descritto onde di superficiali nei solidi, concetto che \'e9 oggi conosciuto come \'93Onde di Rayleigh\'94. Ha contribuito estensivamente alla fluido dinamica con concetti come il numero di Rayleigh, il flusso di Rayleigh l\'92instabilit\'e1 di Rayleigh-Taylor e il criterio di Rayleigh per la stabilit\'e0 dei flussi di Taylor-Couette. La sua derivazione della legge di Rayleigh-Jeans per la radiazione classica di corpo nero ha giocato un ruolo importante per la nascita della quantomeccanica.\
